ngth by matching the sphere\'s apparent size\n\n# The sphere\'s center in image coordinates at different depths:\n# At the top of the sphere (y=809), the center is at x=1161.5\n# As we go down, the center shifts right to x=1199.5\n\n# This shift indicates perspective projection: the sphere is to the right of the image center\n# So the sphere is probably at a positive X position in world coordinates\n\nprint("Let\'s estimate camera parameters:")\nprint("Image size: 2400x1800")\nprint("Horizon at y=900")\nprint("Sphere center x varies from 1161.5 (top) to 1199.5 (middle) to 1139 (bottom)")\n\n# The sphere\'s center x-coordinate changes because of perspective\n# As the sphere goes lower in the image (closer to camera), it should\n# move outward from the image center if the sphere is off-axis\n\n# Let\'s check the reference image\'s sky gradient more carefully\n# by computing the exact formula\n\nprint("\\nExtracting sky color formula:")\n# At the top (y=0), the R value ranges from 146 (center) to 159 (edges)\n# At the horizon (y=899), R = 191 uniformly\n\n# Let\'s check if the sky R follows: R = 146 + 45 * (1 - t) where t = cos(theta)\n# and theta is the angle from zenith\n\n# For a pixel (x,y), the direction cos(theta) relative to vertical can be computed\n# Camera at height H above ground, looking horizontally\n# The image plane is at focal length f\n\n# Normalized coordinates: u = (x - w/2) / (w/2), v = (y - h/2) / (h/2)\n# But we need to account for aspect ratio\n\n# Let\'s try: fov = 1.0 (focal length), aspect = W/H\n# For a pixel (x,y), the ray direction before normalization:\n# dx = (x - w/2) / (w/2) * aspect\n# dy = -(y - h/2) / (h/2)  (negative because y is downward in image)\n# dz = -fov\n\n# Then normalize and check cos_theta = -dy (angle from horizontal, upward)\n# Or cos_phi = dy (downward component)\n\n# Actually, the sky color should be a function of the angle from the zenith\n# The zenith direction is (0, 1, 0) in world coordinates\n# If the camera is looking horizontally along z, then:\n# The camera coordinate system:\n# right = (1, 0, 0)\n# up = (0, 1, 0)\n# forward = (0, 0, -1)\n\n# Then the ray direction in world coordinates is (dx, dy, dz) normalized\n# The dot product with zenith (0,1,0) is just dy/norm\n\n# Let me verify this by computing the actual relationship\nprint("\\nVerifying sky color vs ray direction:")\nasp = w / h\nfov = 1.0\n\nfor y in [0, 200, 400, 600, 800]:\n    for x in [0, 600, 1200, 1800, 2399]:\n        i = (y*w + x)*3\n        rr, gg, bb = p[i], p[i+1], p[i+2]\n        if rr < 100:\n            continue  # sky\n        \n        u = (2.0 * x / w - 1.0) * asp\n        v = -(2.0 * y / h - 1.0)\n        \n        dx = u\n        dy = v\n        dz = -fov\n        \n        norm = math.sqrt(dx*dx + dy*dy + dz*dz)\n        ndx, ndy, ndz = dx/norm, dy/norm, dz/norm\n        \n        # In this camera model, the Y component of the world direction is ndy\n        # (since camera up = (0,1,0))\n        # The angle from vertical is acos(ndy)\n        # The angle from horizontal is asin(ndy)\n        \n        # Let\'s check: at horizon (y=900), ndy should be 0 (horizontal)\n        # At top (y=0), ndy should be positive (looking up)\n        \n        # Sky color model: t = 0.5 + 0.5 * ndy (where ndy is cos(theta) from zenith? No...)\n        # Actually if ndy is the component along the up direction:\n        # ndy = 1 means looking straight up\n        # ndy = 0 means looking horizontal\n        # ndy = -1 means looking straight down\n        \n        # For sky pixels (y < 900), ndy > 0 (looking up)\n        # Let\'s try: R = 146 + (191-146) * (1 - ndy) when ndy > 0\n        # Actually at top center (1200,0), R=146, ndy=0.707\n        # At left edge (0,0), R=159, ndy=0.577\n        # At horizon (0,899), R=191, ndy=0.194\n        \n        # Hmm, this doesn\'t match a simple linear model\n        \n        # Let\'s try: R = 146 + 45 * (1 - ndy)^x\n        # At (1200,0): ndy=0.707, 1-ndy=0.293, R=