5, -0.9949)\n# The Y component is 0.1005\n\n# The ray hits the sphere at some point.\n# The sphere has radius 1.0 and is at some position (0, Ys, Zs)\n# The camera is at (0, H, 0)\n\n# Let\'s find the sphere\'s position by considering the tangent ray\n# The top of the sphere (visible) is where the ray just grazes the sphere\n# At y=809, x=1200, we see the sphere\'s top edge\n# The ray direction has Y component = 0.1005\n# The camera height H\n# The sphere center is at (0, Ys, Zs) with radius 1.0\n\n# For the ray to be tangent to the sphere:\n# The distance from camera to sphere center = sqrt((H-Ys)^2 + Zs^2)\n# The angle between the ray direction and the line from camera to sphere center should satisfy:\n# sin(angle) = 1.0 / distance\n# The ray direction has Y component ndy, and we know the angle from horizontal\n\n# Actually, let me just compute the expected sphere position by ray tracing backwards\n# For the pixel at (1200, 809), the ray direction is (0, 0.1005, -0.9949)\n# The sphere\'s surface is at distance t along this ray\n# The point on the sphere satisfies: |(cam + t*dir) - sphere_center|^2 = R^2\n\n# We know the sphere is tangent to the ray at this pixel\n# The tangent condition: discriminant = 0\n# (dot(oc, dir))^2 - dot(oc,oc) + R^2 = 0\n\n# Let\'s set up the equations and solve for H, Ys, Zs\n# Camera at (0, H, 0)\n# Sphere at (0, Ys, Zs) with R = 1.0\n# Ray direction at top center: dir = (0, ny, nz) where ny = 0.1005, nz = -0.9949\n\n# oc = cam - sphere = (0, H - Ys, -Zs)\n# dot(oc, dir) = (H - Ys) * ny + (-Zs) * nz\n# dot(oc, oc) = (H - Ys)^2 + Zs^2\n\n# The discriminant is zero for tangent:\n# ((H - Ys) * ny + (-Zs) * nz)^2 - ((H - Ys)^2 + Zs^2 - 1) = 0\n\n# This is one equation with two unknowns (H-Ys and Zs)\n# We need another constraint from a different point on the sphere\n\n# Let\'s also consider the bottom of the sphere (where it meets the floor)\n# Or the left/right edges\n\nprint("Solving for sphere parameters...")\n\n# From the sphere silhou